  "prompt": "Can one resign from the Indian Army any time they want?",
  "response": "In the Indian Army, resigning or leaving service is not as simple as in civilian jobs. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Regular Commission Officers:\n- Cannot resign at will\n- Must serve a mandatory minimum service period\n- Can seek premature retirement after completing a specific tenure\n- Resignation requires approval from higher authorities\n\n2. Short Service Commission (SSC) Officers:\n- Can leave after completing their initial service period (usually 10-14 years)\n- Have more flexibility in leaving compared to regular commission officers\n\n3. Enlisted Personnel (Soldiers/Jawans):\n- Have limited options to leave before completing their contractual service period\n- Typically serve for a fixed term (usually 15-17 years)\n- Voluntary retirement or premature discharge is subject to strict conditions\n\n4. Conditions for Resignation/Premature Release:\n- Must provide valid reasons\n- Subject to disciplinary and service regulations\n- Might require paying compensation or serving a penalty\n\n5. Medical Grounds:\n- Can be discharged/released on medical grounds if found unfit for service\n\nThe process is complex and depends on individual circumstances, rank, and service conditions. Each case is evaluated individually by military authorities.",
